It is sometimes difficult to assess until to what point in time the numbers were collected. The previous post on cholera in Yemen reported that MSF was closing many of its treatment centers because of the decreasing cases but for epidemiological week 43, there were still 26 137 new cases, averaging 3734 cases PER DAY. At some level, it is hard to wrap my head around that this is less than earlier in the epidemic.

In 2015 http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/250142/1/WER9138.pdf, WHO reported a total of 172 454 cases worldwide in 42 countries.
In 2016 http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/258910/1/WER9236.pdf, the total number of cases was 132 121 from 38 countries.

This continuing, record-breaking cholera disaster in Yemen is only about a bit more than 6 months old and is 6.74 times the total number of global cases of 2016, and 2.61 times the entire peak year of the Haiti outbreak (2011) of 340 311 cases. The low case fatality rate of 0.26 percent might suggest that some of the diarrhea may be non-cholera. There are now as many cases in over 6 months than in the entire 7 years of the Haitian cholera disaster. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5420642,126.]
